						<summary>

						

						<p>On two pillars set up in front of Dantēśvara temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Jagadēkabhūshaṇa Dhārāvarsha: Śaka 982: 1060 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This damaged inscription furnishes the details of date viz., Śaka 982, Sārvari, Kārthika śu 5, Monday corresponding to 1060 A.D., October 2.</p>						

						<p>The details referring to the [Telugu]-Chōḷa chief Chandrāditya and his pious acts are identical with those mentioned in the sequel in an inscription of this king. (<hi rend="italic">A.R.Ep.,</hi> 1908, No. 334; <hi rend="italic">S.I.I.,</hi> Vol. X, No. 645.). The portion mentioning the names of witnesses to the grant is damaged (Text lines 90105). Only the names of Malli-seṭṭi and Daṇḍīśvara-naṁbi could be traced from the extant portion. The name Kētāchāri seems to be the engraver of this record.</p>						

						<p>Published in <hi rend="italic">South Indian Inscriptions,</hi> Vol. X, No. 644.</p>						

						</summary>
